1.2 Get the data, bo1s and g4ls

Yeah, this chunk is to get the data and plot it, you know we cant keep without it!

#Loading our stocks
#install.packages("quantmod")
library(quantmod)
library(ggplot2)

pbr <- getSymbols("PBR", src = "yahoo", from = "2013-01-01", to = "2020-01-01", auto.assign = FALSE)

Good old returns, as you can see, everything looks nice and ready for our analysis.

It, seems ok, lets take a look at the returns

pbr_ret = CalculateReturns(pbr[,6])

#Honey in the chupet

Do not forget, boys, when youre calculating returns, you are losing one degree of freedom, so the first price in your dataset is going to be null, mmk?

Now, daily returns seems pretty noisy and hard to analyse, here you may want some denoising in your data. The literature here talks about many different ways in capturing the signal of the returns, in this specific case were going to use the rolling volatility of the returns. Another one that you could make is the exponential smooth for example, its pretty common in daily data analysis.

# Compute the rolling 1 month estimate of annualized volatility
chart.RollingPerformance(R = pbr_ret["2000::2020"], width = 22,
     FUN = "sd.annualized", scale = 252, main = "One month rolling volatility")

Now we got it! Can you feel? Can you see? I see trends, and as far as we want, capturing trends of volatility seems a good stuff, remember, we are trying to look our next step volatility, how does it looks like? Its going to be going up or down?

Take a look at our errors, how they behave?

# Compute the mean daily return
m <- mean(pbr_ret[-1])

# Define the series of prediction errors
e <- pbr_ret[-1,1] - m

# Plot the absolute value of the prediction errors
plot(abs(e), main = "Absolute errors")

Lets take a look at the autocorrelation function

# Plot the acf of the absolute prediction errors
acf(abs(e), main = "Absolute errors ACF")

1.3 Finally lets garch

#Our beloved package
library(rugarch)


# Specify a standard GARCH model with constant mean
garchspec <- ugarchspec(mean.model = list(armaOrder = c(0,0)),
                         variance.model = list(model = "sGARCH"), 
                         distribution.model = "norm")

# Estimate the model
garchfit <- ugarchfit(data = pbr_ret[-1], spec = garchspec)

# Use the method sigma to retrieve the estimated volatilities 
garchvol <- sigma(garchfit)

# Plotting our model volatility
plot(garchvol)

Oh great, how does it seems in numbers?

# Compute unconditional volatility
sqrt(uncvariance(garchfit))
## [1] 0,03324343
# Print last 10 ones in garchvol
tail(garchvol, 10)

2 Prediction time!

# Forecast volatility 5 days ahead and add 
garchforecast <- ugarchforecast(fitORspec = garchfit, 
                     n.ahead = 5)

# Extract the predicted volatilities and print them
print(sigma(garchforecast))
##     2019-12-31
## T+1 0,02103637
## T+2 0,02130905
## T+3 0,02157362
## T+4 0,02183046
## T+5 0,02207992
